1.Difference between C & C++:
C-procedure oriented language(step by step approach)
C++-both procedural and object oriented language.

C-function driven language
C++-object driven language.
Array:
 It is a collection of similar data items stored in the consecutive memory locations.
 Array index always starts with 0.
Types:
1D array,multiDimensional array.

1D array-it consists of only one row and one or more columns (or) consists of only one column and one or more rows. Eg: data type arrayName[int size];

2D array-it consists of one or more rows and columns.Eg:data type arrayName[int size][int size];

4.Swap 2 number without using temporary variable:

#include <stdio.h>
void swap(int a,int b);
int main()
{
     int a,b;
    printf("Enter two numbers:");
    scanf("%d %d",&a,&b);
    printf("Before swapping:");
    printf("%d %d",a,b);
    swap(a,b);
    return 0;
}
void swap(int a,int b)
{
    a=a+b;
    b=a-b;
    a=a-b;
    printf("\nAfter swapping:");
    printf("%d %d",a,b);
}

5.Sorting:

#include<stdio.h>
void ascendingSort(int a[],int n)
{
    int i,j,t=0;
    for(i=0;i<n-1;i++)
    {
        for(j=i+1;j<n;j++)
        if(a[i]>a[j])
        {
            t=a[i];
            a[i]=a[j];
            a[j]=t;
        }
    }
    for(i=0;i<n;i++)
    {
        printf("%d ",a[i]);
    }
}
void descendingSort(int a[],int n)
{
    int i,j,t=0;
    for(i=0;i<n-1;i++)
    {
        for(j=i+1;j<n;j++)
        if(a[i]<a[j])
        {
            t=a[i];
            a[i]=a[j];
            a[j]=t;
        }
    }
    for(i=0;i<n;i++)
    {
        printf("%d ",a[i]);
    }
}
int main()
{
    int n=5,a[5]={3,4,1,5,2};
    ascendingSort(a,n);
    printf("\n");
    descendingSort(a,n);
    return 0;
}

6.Pointers:

It is a variable used to store address of another variable.

Pointers are used with call by reference. "*,&" opearators are used in implement pointers.

int a--variable,int *a--pointer variable.

Types:

Null pointer-that points to nothing-->int *a=NULL;

Void pointer-it is not allied with any data types-->int x=10; void *a=&x;

Wild pointer-uninitialized pointers-->int *a;

Dangling pointer-points to deleted memory reference

Near pointer-used to store 16 bit addresses means within current segment on a 16 bit machine

Far pointer-it  is typically 32 bit that can access memory outside current segment

7.Fibonacci with recursion:

#include<stdio.h>
int fib(int n);
int main()
{
    int n;
 printf("Enter number");
 scanf("%d",&n);
 printf(fib(n));
 return 0;
}
int fib(int n)
{
    if(n==1&&n!=0)
      return 0;
     else if(n==2)
      return 1;
     else
     {
      return (fib(n-1)+fib(n-2));
     }
}

8.Array and structure:

 Array is used to store same data type elements whereas structure is iused to store elements of different datatypes.

syntax: datatype array_name [int size]

           struct structure_name

         {

         members;
        }structure variable;
9.Union and structure:
Both are used to store elements of different data types but memory allocation in structure consists of memory size of all elements whereas in union element woth highest memory bytes is allocated.

macro:
 is a name given to a variable or small piece of code/block of program
 lifetime-throughout the program,no semicolon at end **********
 when i use the macros in program it replace macro name with its body/macro expression in that place
 to use multiple statement we can use \ at end of one line.
 # define-keyword
 #define PI 3.14                //PI should be capital,no semicolon at end
 #define MAX(a,b) (a>b)?(a):(b) //no semicolon at end,NO SPACE ALLOWED BETWEEN NAME AND PARAMETER
 #define SQR(x) (x*x)   crt
